South African Stocks Fall: Sasol Drops as Oil Industry Strike Hits Secunda

-- B y   S t e p h e n   G u n n i o n
-- 
2011-07-18T16:22:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-18/south-african-stocks-arcelormittal-metmar-ltd-sasol-move.html
The FTSE/JSE  Africa  All Share Index
ended at its lowest in a week, falling 416.84 or 1.3 percent, to
31,871.59 by the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  Anglo American Plc (AGL)  , the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of the benchmark  stock index , fell for
a third day, dropping 5 rand, or 1.5 percent, to 326 rand.
Copper for three month delivery fell as much as 0.6 percent to
$9,612 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange on concern that
 Europe  and the U.S. are no closer to solving their respective
debt crises, dimming prospects for economic growth.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  , the world’s largest mining
company, closed at its lowest in three weeks, falling 3.70 rand,
or 1.4 percent, to 256.50 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (ANG)  , Africa’s largest gold
producer, closed at its highest in seven weeks, gaining 7.50
rand, or 2.5 percent, to 314 rand. Gold gained for an 11th day,
rising to a record above $1,600 an ounce, in its longest winning
streak since 1980 as debt concerns in Europe and the U.S.
boosted demand for the metal as a protection of wealth.  Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI)  , Africa’s second-biggest producer
of the metal, closed at its highest since June 1, climbing 1.98
rand, or 1.9 percent, to 109.01 rand.  Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR SJ), Africa’s third-largest
gold producer, advanced 98 cents, or 1 percent, to 99.66 rand,
its highest close since April 26.  ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd. (ACL)  , Africa’s largest
steelmaker, closed at its lowest since November 2010, dropping
2.25 rand, or 2.9 percent, to 75.10 rand. About 320,000 workers
in  South Africa ’s metals and engineering industries will return
to work after employers agreed to a wage increase of 10 percent,
above an earlier offer of 7 percent.  Metmar Ltd. (MML)  , a South African mining investment
company, gained 15 cents, or 4.7 percent, to 3.35 rand. The
group said earnings would be improved by its purchase of a
further 60 percent interest in Eastern Belt Chrome Mines.  Shoprite Holdings Ltd. (SHP)  , South Africa’s largest
retailer by market value, fell for the first day in five,
dropping 1.89 rand, or 1.8 percent, to 102.26 rand. Sales
increased by 7.3 percent to 72.3 billion rand in the 12 months
through June, the group said in an operational update, lower
than the 73.6 billion rand median estimate of seven analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg.    Sasol Ltd. (SOL)  , the world’s largest maker of motor
fuel from coal, dropped 7.11 rand, or 2 percent, to 352.64 rand.
The  oil company  lowered production rates at parts of its Secunda
plant in South Africa “in the interest of safety” amid a
strike over wages, the company said in an e-mailed statement.  To contact the reporter on this story:
